3-4463-b50e-c7443a19adc3","name":"17.4","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n He has, in his stupendous works, left the character of his divinity, and ‘tis our own weakness only that hinders us from discerning it.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"454e400d-6255-457a-a08c-54865991ebfb","name":"17.5","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n ‘Tis what he himself is pleased to tell us, “That he manifests his invisible operations to us by those that are visible.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"4adbe300-980a-43e8-bf84-88dd9385154d","name":"17.6","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n” Sebond applied himself to this laudable and noble study, and demonstrates to us that there is not any part or member of the world that disclaims or derogates from its maker.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"f781c413-73bb-4540-9848-d88fd686e01e","name":"17.7","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n It were to do wrong to the divine goodness, did not the universe consent to our belief.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"0f9ff54a-99ec-4555-82b2-94be3d640a76","name":"17.8","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n The heavens, the earth, the elements, our bodies and our souls,—all things concur to this; we have but to find out the way to use them; they instruct us, if we are capable of instruction.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"add764f4-009d-4456-81e3-34ac9706d06e","name":"17.9","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n For this world is a sacred temple, into which man is introduced, there to contemplate statues, not the works of a mortal hand, but such as the divine purpose has made the objects of sense; the sun, the stars, the water, and the earth, to represent those that are intelligible to us.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"fcbeb4a8-4027-4aff-b4df-b081b1200c2c","name":"17.10","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n “The invisible tilings of God,” says St.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"d641a0eb-22a8-452b-b9dc-e6d7677e1083","name":"17.11","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Paul, “appear by the creation of the world, his eternal wisdom and divinity being considered by his works.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}