a29a-39d2524e409e","name":"paragraph67","children":[{"idx":"559ce59e-729c-472b-a066-e9aa30cba2fb","name":"67.0","NodeDescription":"///t\r\nFor instance, take the fox, the people of Thrace make use of when they wish to pass over the ice of some frozen river, and turn him out before them to that purpose; when we see him lay his ear upon the bank of the river, down to the ice, to listen if from a more remote or nearer distance he can hear the noise of the waters’ current, and, according as he finds by that the ice to be of a less or greater thickness, to retire or advance,—have we not reason to believe thence that the same rational thoughts passed through his head that we should have upon the like occasions; and that it is a ratiocination and consequence, drawn from natural sense, that that which makes a noise runs, that which runs is not frozen, what is not frozen is liquid, and that which is liquid yields to impression!t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"33244cc2-8700-45cd-b0ea-bea1c094ee32","name":"67.1","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n For to attribute this to a mere quickness of the sense of hearing, without reason and consequence, is a chimra that cannot enter into the imagination.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"1037535a-d3e9-461f-9a9a-3b630334af74","name":"67.2","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n We are to suppose the same of the many sorts of subtleties and inventions with which beasts secure themselves from, and frustrate, the enterprizes we plot against them.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}]},{"idx":"ff59049d-6db1-4db5-95b8-ab526cd0e203","name":"paragraph68","children":[{"idx":"531ee626-ac8d-41d5-ab28-fde8a848f9c4","name":"68.0","NodeDescription":"///t\r\nAnd if we will make an advantage even of this, that it is in our power to seize them, to employ them in our service, and to use them at our pleasure, ‘tis still but the same advantage we have over one another.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"f66e61c8-b980-4d72-934c-96ff1734a935","name":"68.1","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n We have our slave