 suffers himself to be carried on there bv the force of reason.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"1f45da1d-97bd-4d60-bc61-465ea7498ef1","name":"75.4","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n This sally, purely logical, and this use of propositions divided and conjoined, and the right enumeration of parts, is it not every whit as good that the dog knows all this of himself as well as from Trapezuntius?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}]},{"idx":"414fb7ed-7d76-46eb-95d8-1e6993ee42b0","name":"paragraph76","children":[{"idx":"9f50f9af-3514-4452-850a-71d6bb427bd8","name":"76.0","NodeDescription":"///t\r\nAnimals are not incapable, however, of being instructed after our method.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"42b1f786-48a3-45bf-ad30-ab45748623e4","name":"76.1","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n We teach blackbirds, ravens, pies, and parrots, to speak: and the facility wherewith we see they lend us their voices, and render both them and their breath so supple and pliant, to be formed and confined within a certain number of letters and syllables, does evince that they have a reason within, which renders them so docile and willing to learn.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"8e9dc70c-79fe-4d49-b10c-f5b4715b0ce1","name":"76.2","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Everybody, I believe, is glutted with the several sorts of tricks that tumblers teach their dogs; the dances, where they do not miss any one cadence of the sound they hear; the several various motions and leaps they make them perform by the command of a word.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"e3fad087-2f6a-427d-b65d-76b126babb2d","name":"76.3","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n But I observe this effect with the greatest admiration, which nevertheless is very common, in the dogs that lead the blind, both in the country and in cities: I have taken notice how they stop at certain doors, where they are wont to receive alms; how they avoid the encounter of coaches and carts, even there where they have sufficient room to pass; I have seen them, by the trench of a town, forsake a plai