b93b9-6ed7-461d-aa65-1e00c4a30b3a","name":"231.6","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n If you maintain that snow is black, they will argue on the contrary that it is white; if you say it is neither the one nor the other, they will maintain that it is both.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"bb929ad6-288b-4447-823c-1bbebb4bcc44","name":"231.7","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n If you hold, of certain judgment, that you know nothing, they will maintain that you do.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"c223c176-9a0e-43ef-b273-bf1fdadadf8c","name":"231.8","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Yea, and if by an affirmative axiom you assure them that you doubt, they will argue against you that you doubt not; or that you cannot judge and determine that you doubt.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"0bf0fdf9-7a98-4d82-891e-14ba793ec94d","name":"231.9","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n And by this extremity of doubt, which jostles itself, they separate and divide themselves from many opinions, even of those they have several ways maintained, both concerning doubt and ignorance.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"4fe87667-2e56-47d9-b272-2658c9ddaf4f","name":"231.10","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n “Why shall not they be allowed to doubt,” say they, “as well as the dogmatists, one of whom says green, another yellow?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"204bb498-af87-4ea0-a6f4-2a5ba53c0db6","name":"231.11","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Can any thing be proposed to us to grant, or deny, which it shall not be permitted to consider as ambiguous?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"77df5a37-5b0b-4853-8ee3-4dd6c207aa78","name":"231.12","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n” And where others are carried away, either by the custom of their country, or by the instruction of parents, or by accident, as by a tempest, without judgment and without choice, nay, and for the most part before the age of discretion, to such and such an opinion, to the sect whether Stoic or Epicurean, with which they are prepossessed, enslaved, and fast bound, as to a thing they cannot forsake: Ad quamcumque disciplinant, velut tempestate, delati, ad earn, tanquam ad saxum, adhorescunt; “every one cleaves to the doctrine he has happened upon, as to a rock against which he has been thrown by tempest;” why shall not these likewise be permitted to maintain their liberty, and consider things without obligation or slavery?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"979d21d4-5e39-49c7-ba9b-3a7ea359c3d4","name":"231.13","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n hoc liberiores et solutiores, quod integra illis est judicandi potestas: “in this more unconstrained and free, because they have the greater power of judging.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"d2061444-837f-4378-bcf0-a8e78e90eaab","name":"231.14","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n” Is it not of some advantage to be disengaged from the necessity that curbs others?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"3e317bb0-87b4-4f63-a225-78f89b44b326","name":"231.15","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Is it not better to remain in suspense than to entangle one’s self in the innumerable errors that human fancy has produced?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"493165c3-3483-4882-8f7b-3fbb79c9d053","name":"231.16","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Is it not much better to suspend one’s persuasion than to intermeddle with these wrangling and seditious divisions: “What shall I choose?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"545ac0a9-8fa5-453b-b405-5df4a5130748","name":"231.17","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n” “What you please, provided you will choose.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"2f8a83ea-f1fb-4459-9ad9-52d9b42463c1","name":"231.18","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n” A very foolish answer; but such a one, nevertheless, as all dogmatism seems to point at, and by which we are not permitted to be ignorant of what we are ignorant of.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}]},{"idx":"b54b80ca-8e0e-44cf-96e3-67a63abcec88","name":"paragraph232","children":[{"idx":"48a1f996-5109-4020-9950-94572ac8fb96","name":"232.0","NodeDescription":"///t\r\nTake the most eminent side, that of the greatest reputation; it will never be so sure t