ac-d4ebbc8641c3","name":"326.1","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Mirum quo procdat improbitas cordis humani, parvulo aliquo intritata successu.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"d724adfe-8958-4f4d-af86-fdd1e0752664","name":"326.2","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n “‘Tis wonderful to what the wickedness of man’s heart will proceed, if elevated with the least success.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"9097c43f-e0df-487c-8dc1-054bb003ca5a","name":"326.3","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n” How magisterially and insolently does Epicurus reprove the Stoics, for maintaining that the truly good and happy being appertained only to God, and that the wise man had nothing but a shadow and resemblance of it!t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"48f002f3-e0ca-4039-bc48-42d14c5003ca","name":"326.4","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n How temerariously have they bound God to destiny (a thing which, by my consent, none that bears the name of a Christian shall ever do again)!t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"bc1cd491-07b1-4a79-9409-33d1f4fd8e7f","name":"326.5","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n and Thales, Plato, and Pythagoras have enslaved him to necessity.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"481e942f-2474-4afd-a0f3-98c4ddb3a1f9","name":"326.6","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n This arrogance of attempting to discover God with our eyes has been the cause that an eminent person among us has attributed to the Divinity a corporal form; and is the reason of what happens to us every day, of attributing to God important events, by a particular assignment.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"1f60289e-4b86-4da0-8abf-dbb5d422e27c","name":"326.7","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Because they weigh with us, they conclude that they also weigh with him, and that he has a more intent and vigilant regard to them than to others of less moment to us or of ordinary course: Magna Dii curant, parva negligunt: “The gods are concerned at great matters, but slight the small.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"4632cafb-6854-4c15-bc0a-467b41c578a2","name":"326.8","NodeDescription":"