 law itself has, they say, legitimate fictions, whereon it builds the truth of its justice); she gives us in presupposition, and for current pay, things which she herself informs us were invented; for these epicycles, eccentrics, and concentrics, which astrology makes use of to carry on the motions of the stars, she gives us for the best she could invent upon that subject; as also, in all the rest, philosophy presents us not that which really is, or what she really believes, but what she has contrived with the greatest and most plausible likelihood of truth, and the quaintest invention.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"e1d9dda6-8413-4b63-b268-0e1f882752cc","name":"367.10","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n Plato, upon the discourse of the state of human bodies and those of beasts, says, “I should know that what I have said is truth, had I the confirmation of an oracle; but this I will affirm, that what I have said is the most likely to be true of any thing I could say.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}]},{"idx":"3b64284b-ab15-4580-8098-deb17fe8ce99","name":"paragraph368","children":[{"idx":"2bfde3d3-4047-4d02-b3d8-9d58fd374223","name":"368.0","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n‘Tis not to heaven only that art sends her ropes, engines, and wheels; let us consider a little what she says of us ourselves, and of our contexture.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}]},{"idx":"e56f9ac1-fca3-4b3f-a937-35341b52725b","name":"paragraph369","children":[{"idx":"f0d33599-193e-4f75-9206-93659aab5cc0","name":"369.0","NodeDescription":"///t\r\nThere is not more retrogradation, trepidation, accession, recession, and astonishment, in the stars and celestial bodies, than they have found out in this poor little human body.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"7d75f5b5-4a40-4915-a3da-0208126c88a9","name":"369.1","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n In earnest, they have good reason, upon that very account, to call it the little world, so many tools and parts have they employed to erect and build it.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"dde24ab6-8bc2-48b6-b374-971989b1dccb","name":"369.2","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n To assist the motions they see in man, and the various functions that we find in ourselves, in how many parts have they divided the soul, in how many places lodged it?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"fdfbf92e-b983-47a5-8b3d-1abbe11d6a8a","name":"369.3","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n in how many orders have they divided, and to how many stories have they raised this poor creature, man, besides those that are natural and to be perceived?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"1e7d844a-96e4-494a-94a9-affdec62040b","name":"369.4","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n And how many offices and vocations have they assigned him?t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"ad5663b7-588a-4a60-97d4-deb8d343c834","name":"369.5","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n They make it an imaginary public thing.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"b4436cf7-9432-4d19-8d1a-e77afc7be1ea","name":"369.6","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n ‘Tis a subject that they hold and handle; and they have full power granted to them to rip, place, displace, piece, and stuff it, every one according to his own fancy, and yet they possess it not They cannot, not in reality only, but even in dreams, so govern it that there will not be some cadence or sound that will escape their architecture, as enormous as it is, and botched with a thousand false and fantastic patches.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"},{"idx":"5d6cb8d8-87d0-4ffe-9397-815decfc49e7","name":"369.7","NodeDescription":"///t\r\n And it is not reason to excuse them; for though we are satisfied with painters when they paint heaven, earth, seas, mountains, and remote islands, that they give us some slight mark of them, and, as of things unknown, are content with a faint and obscure description; yet when they come and draw us after life, or any other creature which is known and familiar to us, we then require of them a perfect and exact representation of lineaments and colours, and despise them if they fail in it.t///\r\n///h\r\nh///"}]}]},{"name":"tmp.49","c